<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-03-28T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-03-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="1743" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1743">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.0145/6.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 506.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">St. Petersburg</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-03-28">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 28, 1911</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In reply to the Department’s instruction
                            No. 148 of the 11th instant, concerning the Russian law extending to
                            twelve miles from low-water mark the area of supervision by the Russian
                            customs authorities, I have the honor to state that the only information
                            on the subject which the Minister for Foreign Affairs has so far been
                            able to give me was another copy of the Law of December 10/23, 1909
                            (forwarded with my despatch No. 363 of September 30, 1910).</p>
                        <p>I have been unable to secure copies of the notes exchanged by the Russian
                            and British Governments on this subject, which is still under
                            discussion, though I had already asked that they be shown for your
                            confidential information.</p>
                        <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">W. W. Rockhill.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>